snippet.textDisplay: The Facebook thing is due to EU laws on data protection and while you might say: "But how does this affect the USA!?" Well, as the data that is collected in the EU, is ultimately sent back to the US, it needs to comply with EU data protection laws in the country that the data is going to end up and be stored in, which in this case is the States! So they have a choice of amending their entire data collection policy, withdrawing from the EU market, or having a different operating procedure in different continents. Obviously, the first choice there makes the most sense, as it means they only have to keep up to date with one policy, rather than multiple and they get to continue operating within the EU!

snippet.textDisplay: Slight correction to the news surrounding the UK's COVID blunder. Although yes, Excel is capable of handling one million-plus rows, the developers used XLS, an antiquated file format dating back to 1987 and superseded in 2007. As a consequence, each template could handle only about 65,000 rows of data and since each test result created several rows of data, in practice it meant that each template was limited to about 1,400 cases. Why Excel was deemed as a suitable replacement for actual database management software is beyond me.
